%I A395370 #22 May 17 2026 16:26:40
%S A395370 1,1,5,39,332,4337,65355,1084401,20253143,407155395,8669715855
%N A395370 a(n) is the number of pairs (B->A, C->A) of non-intersecting paths in a triangular grid ABC of side n units, such that the distance from the starting point to each point of a path is always increasing.
%C A395370 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles. X axis is defined along AB and Y axis is defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), finishing point B has coordinates (n,0) and C is at (0,n).
%C A395370 Points on the path satisfy x + y <= n, y <= n/2 and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point.
%C A395370 Each of P-path from A to B gives a unique Q-path from B to A and R-path from C to A by transforming a grid point (h,k) on P-path into; (n-h-k,k) on Q-path and (k,n-h-k) on R-path. A Q-path and a R-path do not meet if pair of grid paths does not contain common points other than at starting and finishing.
%H A395370 Pontus von Brömssen, <a href="/A395370/a395370.png">Illustration for n=4</a>.
%H A395370 Pontus von Brömssen, <a href="/A395370/a395370_1.png">Illustration for n=5</a>.
%H A395370 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A395370/a395370_1.txt">Python code for pairs (Q,R) of strings of coordinates</a>
%e A395370 n = 2 has only one way of reaching a corner from other two corners:
%e A395370 Grid paths from B to A:
%e A395370  Q1:{(2,0), (1,1), (0,1), (0,0)},
%e A395370  Q2:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,1), (0,0)},
%e A395370  Q3:{(2,0), (1,0), (0,0)}.
%e A395370 Grid paths from C to A:
%e A395370  R1:{(0,2), (1,1), (1,0), (0,0)},
%e A395370  R2:{(0,2), (0,1), (1,0), (0,0)},
%e A395370  R3:{(0,2), (0,1), (0,0)}.
%e A395370 Set of valid pairs of grid paths:
%e A395370  {(Q3,R3)}.
%e A395370 Therefore a(2) = 1.
%Y A395370 Cf. A394698, A394098, A395035, A395369, A395371.
